Some data gathered in André Nogueira's research are noteworthy (<htcite0>):
- The main focus was on crimes against the religious order;
- Even members of the clergy were punished. One of the main crimes, according to religious traditions, was the fact that priests kept *“concubines”*, who received inheritances after the priests' death;
- Economic crimes were also judged, such as *"abuses in the rental values of beasts, oxen, and cows"*;
- Practices of *"witchcraft and magical cures"*;
- People who had a *"sharp tongue"* causing disturbances in the community.

#### *Devassa* in Espirito Santo

In the eighth edition of the *Revista Genea*, published in <htdate0>, researcher and genealogist Gilber Rubim Rangel presented data on the *devassa* process of the Religious of the Society of Jesus in Espírito Santo (<htcite1>).

His publication lists several indigenous individuals identified with the surname Dias.
